kWljFmp0KiOOa3Ceh6fK6eC3ocyK7Femo9mGGI-44GHZ8PhcMUel_KI3iNUwcRB28Lki5nqo0bX_IzmGVK7qF_QLQYd5xwyN8WBrT7ktD0GfWjPQPZ0qkj78oJvS1Rn53UzmKAjCAfwbPbAKOUllxqV8mgfda-qs9CTLiaSpI7T_u7uw7VTEKUTa20M4MDxfBYKQyAep41axgre-IJfUywvhAAYqkN7n_il--kvxz3tEl2iocWgkbx1x6_kM3ysV6R0uM7y3mju7NmOcv4zOIi3aFQYS4I4Ef6A1XWhahaWr_1_Cv8SWwtPie-di0Xa6sAeFzfU90lrd4kBcaaUYjPxJgrQa9r_--MC-L-BHP1Y540Ty17O0CFN7ozaEAhfeZk_adalL4CEyVzOowa-r_AIwl9lN1AhLqtWaYCuuV5ydHkNmnyIxCgKl_aKOyStTCD_BcQ3kmWzFX2l6sHxYdlQT84_CJHdVXhppSrF-hO2kzMRcUpL4NiLN_duUJw51kgHD881sLYaR6CDbCJ_wLcDuEjsx1JpyLlSIJewdmqhC0keO1wcrW0i7x-bTpI9ViD0IvJbnVYOW8sd5B7LwTB7kYnJqboY16eRoltXulwUdpYfdYZI16ESg2hLm4indwG-VXGxW8BGk4QnNrg==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Java function invocation**\\n\\nI’m considering if I should use Java’s MethodHandles.privateLookupIn to invoke something. This seems like it could provide a way to access private methods or fields in a more controlled manner. I'm curious about its implications and whether it would fit well with what I'm trying to achieve. It might also be useful to look into examples of when this approach is applied. I wonder what are the benefits and potential drawbacks of using this method!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring coverage methods**\\n\\nI'm figuring out the coverage process. It appears that directly invoking methods may not work as expected. I’m wondering if the instrumentation is tracking Class.forName. It might be a question of whether we're calling it on an already loaded class. Maybe the tool reports static call sites and uses JFR for tests. Should I consider adding a static helper in the test package? I'm also evaluating the effects of using Groovy methods. I should investigate more!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating Groovy API usage**\\n\\nI'm exploring how to use Groovy's public API to call a static method by name, considering that this might naturally cover the necessary calls since it runs through Groovy’s runtime instead of Java reflection. I'll need to add the Groovy dependency for `InvokerHelper`. I'll check if Groovy allows invoking package-private static methods since it usually has good access. There's potential to use `GroovySystem` for invoking methods. If direct reflection isn't providing coverage, maybe switching to MethodHandles is the answer. I’m still pondering those access issues, particularly with literals involving `$`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering naming rules**\\n\\nI’m pondering the naming rules for files and classes. It seems like only class names need to follow specific guidelines, while strings can be more flexible. Since the tests are outside the library packages, that shouldn’t be a problem. However, it gets tricky since direct class names are hardcoded, and I wonder if that's an issue. I really want to make sure everything aligns well with the best practices and keep things flexible.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Updating test process**\\n\\nI’m thinking about updating my test. Instead of using external method reflection, I can capture the resolvedClass from the mapper by calling GroovyObject this$dist$invoke$1 on the data. This way, I can avoid using external reflection since I'm only working with the active class. I'll need to import groovy.lang.GroovyObject and remove the Method. Plus, I should record the resolvedClass and add an assertion. This might cover class$ during the mapper execution. Let’s make those adjustments!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_MhKkBl9344nUbf1y8e2080Hy|fc_0652409166806867016a27ef6d240481958781545d4064f7bd", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io_rest_assured/rest_assured/RestAssuredResponseOptionsGroovyImplAnonymous1Test.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.InputStream;\nimport java.lang.reflect.Method;\nimport java.net.HttpURLConnection;", "newText": "import java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.InputStream;\nimport java.net.HttpURLConnection;"}, {"oldText": "import com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpExchange;\nimport com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpServer;\nimport io.restassured.common.mapper.DataToDeserialize;", "newText": "import com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpExchange;\nimport com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpServer;\nimport groovy.lang.GroovyObject;\nimport io.restassured.common.mapper.DataToDeserialize;"}, {"oldText": "            assertThat(capturedResponseBody.byteArrayBody()).isEqualTo(RESPONSE_BODY);\n            assertThat(capturedResponseBody.inputStreamBody()).isEqualTo(RESPONSE_BODY);\n\n            Method classHelper = capturedResponseBody.dataImplementationClass().getDeclaredMethod(\n                    \"class$\", String.class);\n            classHelper.setAccessible(true);\n            Class<?> resolvedClass = (Class<?>) classHelper.invoke(\n                    null, DataToDeserialize.class.getName());\n            assertThat(resolvedClass).isEqualTo(DataToDeserialize.class);\n        } finally {", "newText": "            assertThat(capturedResponseBody.byteArrayBody()).isEqualTo(RESPONSE_BODY);\n            assertThat(capturedResponseBody.inputStreamBody()).isEqualTo(RESPONSE_BODY);\n            assertThat(capturedResponseBody.resolvedDataType()).isEqualTo(DataToDeserialize.class);\n        } finally {"}, {"oldText": "            String byteArrayBody,\n            String inputStreamBody,\n            Class<?> dataImplementationClass) {", "newText": "            String byteArrayBody,\n            String inputStreamBody,\n            Class<?> resolvedDataType) {"}, {"oldText": "            DataToDeserialize dataToDeserialize = context.getDataToDeserialize();\n            String inputStreamBody = readBody(context);\n            return new CapturedResponseBody(\n                    stringBody, byteArrayBody, inputStreamBody, dataToDeserialize.getClass());", "newText": "            DataToDeserialize dataToDeserialize = context.getDataToDeser