ime instead of Java reflection. I'll need to add the Groovy dependency for `InvokerHelper`. I'll check if Groovy allows invoking package-private static methods since it usually has good access. There's potential to use `GroovySystem` for invoking methods. If direct reflection isn't providing coverage, maybe switching to MethodHandles is the answer. I’m still pondering those access issues, particularly with literals involving `$`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering naming rules**\\n\\nI’m pondering the naming rules for files and classes. It seems like only class names need to follow specific guidelines, while strings can be more flexible. Since the tests are outside the library packages, that shouldn’t be a problem. However, it gets tricky since direct class names are hardcoded, and I wonder if that's an issue. I really want to make sure everything aligns well with the best practices and keep things flexible.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Updating test process**\\n\\nI’m thinking about updating my test. Instead of using external method reflection, I can capture the resolvedClass from the mapper by calling GroovyObject this$dist$invoke$1 on the data. This way, I can avoid using external reflection since I'm only working with the active class. I'll need to import groovy.lang.GroovyObject and remove the Method. Plus, I should record the resolvedClass and add an assertion. This might cover class$ during the mapper execution. Let’s make those adjustments!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_MhKkBl9344nUbf1y8e2080Hy|fc_0652409166806867016a27ef6d240481958781545d4064f7bd", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io_rest_assured/rest_assured/RestAssuredResponseOptionsGroovyImplAnonymous1Test.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.InputStream;\nimport java.lang.reflect.Method;\nimport java.net.HttpURLConnection;", "newText": "import java.io.IOExcep